<?xml version='1.0' encoding='utf-8'?>
<subsection xml:id="lec-introduccionAlVolumenLiquido" xmlns:xi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XInclude">

<shorttitle>Lección 7 </shorttitle>
<title>Lección 7 -<nbsp/></title>
<title>Introducción al volumen líquido</title>


<!-- ============================================ 
  Objetivos de aprendizaje                        
=================================================  -->

<!-- Frase resumen para estudiante. Originalmente [Student Facing Goals] -->
<introduction component="est-goal"> 
  <p>Aprendamos sobre el volumen líquido.</p>
</introduction>

<!-- Objetivos para el estudiante. Originalmente [Student-Facing Targets] -->
<!-- <objectives component="estudiante">
  <ul>
    <li>[@@@@@@@@@@@@@@]</li>
  </ul>
</objectives> -->

<!-- Objetivos que solo ve el profesor. Originalmente [Teacher Facing Goals] -->
<objectives component="profesor">
  <ul>
    <li><p>[++++++++++++++++]</p></li>
    <li>
      <p>Estimate and compare liquid volumes of containers using informal units and liters.</p>
    </li>
    <li>
      <p>Understand liquid volume as the amount of space that a liquid takes up.</p>
    </li>
  </ul>
</objectives>


<!-- ============================================ 
  Introducción para el profesor                        
=================================================  -->
<introduction component="profesor">

  <!-- Estándares CCSS asociados -->
  <paragraphs>
    <title><custom ref="ccss-leccion-titulo"/></title> 
    <ul>
      <li> 
        <custom ref="ccss-addressing"/>
        <xref ref="ccss-3-MD-A-2" text="custom">3.MD.A.2</xref>
      </li>
    </ul>
    </paragraphs>

  <!-- índice de la lección (automático) -->
  <paragraphs>
    <title><custom ref="timeline-leccion-titulo"/></title>
    <list-of elements="subsubsection reading-questions" scope="subsection"/>
  </paragraphs>

  <!-- Propósito de la lección -->
  <paragraphs>
    <title><custom ref="purpose-leccion-titulo"/></title>
    <p>[+++++++++++++++]</p>
    <p>The purpose of this lesson is to introduce students to the measurement of <term>liquid volume.</term></p>
  </paragraphs>

  <!-- Materiales requeridos -->
  <paragraphs>
    <title><custom ref="materials-leccion-titulo"/></title>
    <ul>
      <li>
        <p>Actividad 1</p>
        <xi:include href="./act-exploracionDeEstimacion-volumenLiquido-mat.ptx"/>
        <!--<xi:include href="./act-exploracionDeEstimacion-volumenLiquido-matCentros.ptx"/>-->
      </li>
      <li>
        <p>Actividad 2</p>
        <xi:include href="./act-volumenLiquidoEnLitros-mat.ptx"/>
        <!--<xi:include href="./act-volumenLiquidoEnLitros-matCentros.ptx"/>-->
      </li>
    </ul>  
  </paragraphs>
  
  <!-- Introducción de la lección (narrative) -->
  <paragraphs>
    <title><custom ref="narrative-leccion-titulo"/></title>
    <p>[+++++++++++++++]</p>
    <p>In previous lessons, students measured and estimated the weight of objects in grams and kilograms. In this lesson, students learn that <term>liquid volume</term> is the amount of space that a liquid takes up and consider the challenges of directly comparing liquid volumes by just looking at them. Students use informal units (such as plastic cups, spoons, and so on) to compare the liquid volume that two containers will hold. Finally, students are introduced to the <term>liter</term> as a metric unit of liquid volume. They create a tool for measuring liquid volume in liters by filling a container and making a mark for each liter as it’s added to the container. A clear container is used so students can see the level of the liquid and a dry erase marker is used so the marks can be erased after the lesson.</p>
    <p>To build a conceptual understanding of liquid volume, it is extremely helpful for students to have firsthand experience of comparing liquids in different containers. To make that possible, some new materials and preparation are required for this lesson.</p>
  </paragraphs>
  
  <!-- Preguntas de reflexión profesor -->
  <paragraphs>
    <title><custom ref="reflection-quest-titulo"/></title>
    <p>[+++++++++++++++]</p>
    <p>What surprised you about student thinking about measurements of liquid volume in the first activity? What strategies did you anticipate? Which did you not anticipate?</p>
  </paragraphs>
</introduction>


